{"@context":"http://iiif.io/api/presentation/3/context.json","id":"https://digbmc.github.io/pta-manifests/phan/phan-20305/manifest.json","type":"Manifest","label":{"none":["PHAN-20305"]},"metadata":[{"label":{"none":["Timestamp"]},"value":{"none":["2:03:05"]}},{"label":{"none":["Film"]},"value":{"none":["Phantom Thread"]}},{"label":{"none":["Distance"]},"value":{"none":["medium shot"]}},{"label":{"none":["Angle"]},"value":{"none":["low"]}},{"label":{"none":["Location"]},"value":{"none":["interior"]}},{"label":{"none":["Movement"]},"value":{"none":["mobile, pan, tilt, tracking"]}},{"label":{"none":["Composition"]},"value":{"none":["three shot"]}}],"summary":{"none":["A woman inspects a model in a showroom."]},"thumbnail":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-20305/tiles/full/300,169/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":169,"width":300}],"homepage":[{"id":"PHAN-20305","type":"Text","format":"text/html","label":{"none":["Object homepage"]}}],"items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-20305/canvas/1","type":"Canvas","height":1080,"width":1920,"label":{"none":["PHAN-20305"]},"thumbnail":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-20305/tiles/full/300,169/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":169,"width":300}],"items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-20305/canvas/1/annopage-1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-20305/canvas/1/annopage-1/anno-1","type":"Annotation","motivation":"painting","target":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-20305/canvas/1","body":{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-20305/tiles/full/1920,1080/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":1080,"width":1920,"service":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-20305/tiles","type":"ImageService3","profile":"http://iiif.io/api/image/3/level0.json"}]}}]}],"annotations":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-20305/canvas/1/page/p1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-20305/canvas/1/2d7cfd3c-3708-4a3f-80d1-960e692727dc","type":"Annotation","motivation":"commenting","body":[{"created":"2026-06-29T14:18:29.179Z","creator":"Ada ","purpose":"commenting","type":"TextualBody","format":"text/html","value":"<p>Alma fills Reynolds’s role in this scene, walking around and examining the dress just as he <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" class=\"Hyperlink SCXW64677682 BCX4\" href=\"https://digbmc.github.io/pt-annotated/items/phan-11442.html\"><u>did</u></a> with the Princess’s wedding dress. The costuming furthers this parallel. Her black vest and white shirt mirror several of his outfits from <a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" class=\"Hyperlink SCXW64677682 BCX4\" href=\"https://ptannotated.com/items/phan-03831.html\"><u>earlier in the film</u></a>. She is no longer merely one of the many interchangeable employees in pristine white coats; she has become his equal.&nbsp;</p>"}],"target":{"type":"SpecificResource","source":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-20305/canvas/1","selector":{"type":"FragmentSelector","conformsTo":"http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/","value":"xywh=pixel:545.3311901913873,182.81250000000006,383.287230861244,752.0947966507177"}}},{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-20305/canvas/1/3450aabf-6748-4f26-8bcb-cef7ffd1411a","type":"Annotation","motivation":"commenting","body":[{"created":"2026-06-29T14:19:20.210Z","creator":"Ada ","purpose":"commenting","type":"TextualBody","format":"text/html","value":"<p>Building on the themes of hauntings and time, Alma says that in this future she takes care of Reynolds’s dresses, “keeping them from dust and ghosts and time.” The House of Woodcock has long been haunted by these elements, but with Alma’s intrusion into the tailor’s life, she can displace the ghost and memory of his mother that have tormented him. The dustiness of his house is likewise cleared away by Alma who tends after his belongings and spaces with great care, much as she refuses to indulge his fussiness—a kind of “dust” that makes everyone choke in the House of Woodcock. Finally, Alma believes she can transcend time and thus make Reynolds’s art eternal by crafting this narrative according to her own vision (her aesthetics) and through her love for him.&nbsp;</p>"}],"target":{"type":"SpecificResource","source":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-20305/canvas/1","selector":{"type":"FragmentSelector","conformsTo":"http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/","value":"xywh=pixel:29.6142344497607,48.936154306219954,270.2018540669855,159.59928229665067"}}}]}]}]}